76561198006899168,Recommended,281610,20656887,"Posted: 21 January, 2016",all,Mr.Gray,"Hello everybody.About myself:RTS player, usually oriented on competetive multiplayer experience (CoH, SupCom, MoW:AS), have limited experience with Homeworld franchise overall but definitely a persone interested in lore.In short:Game is great. It has some issues, but there is no core flaws which can make a game unplayable or effect its replayability. Game core mechanics are pretty deep, It has rich solo experience and well thought-out competetive oriented multiplayer. It is defenitely a Homeworld game from Homeworld developers. You can feel the soul of game universe while playing this game thats for sure. Amount of work those guys put in lore, game details and gameplay is huge and you can be sure that project not gonna be droped like some random moneygrab. Get this game and invest in quality game development.Core mechanicsGame is defenitely self sufficient as Homeworld game and as real time strategy. There are multiple gameplay layers from terrain to unit active abilities and veterancy system. Solid groundbased strategy overall which can be compared to original Company of heroes.Solo campaignStory is rich, gameplay is really immersive. You have great wrighting, voice acting, awesome cutscenes\videos, unit persistance with veterancy system and pretty intence atmosphere overall. Expedition Guide adds alot for lore guys like me. All you need is a bit of imagination and good headset to dive into desert.On the other side difficulty even on classic is not that hard, but game do not hold your hand all the time like TotalBiscuit tells you.MultiplayerInformation about multiplayer was limited before release to say at least and this part of the game come out as a great surprise. You can clearly feel that original Shipbreackers project was oriented on multiplayer. You have 1v1, 2v2 3v3 ladder system with matchmaking and skill tiers. Artifact retreaval game mode in ranked saves this game from passive camping of original annihialtion gamemode of Homeworld multiplayer. Belance is pretty good for a fact that there were no closed\open beta for multyplayer. You can play 2 factions with really good diversity, dont listen to those who tells you that they are all the same. There is no identical units at all and there are huge core differencies in strategy\abilities\unit compositions etc. With great game core mechanics this game have a possibility to became a noticable RTS game like CoH or SupCom. There is no replay and observers system which are essential to form a competetive community around the game. And 5 maps are not enought thats for sure. Devs have a lot of work here if they want to bring this game to competetive standarts.You can look at competetive part of the game here - ""First Ever Shoutcast! Pro 1v1"" from well known Company of Heroes commentatorshttps://youtu.be/XQcZM8-lMMAThat is all i think, hope it was helpfull."
76561198015320747,Not Recommended,281610,33466881,Posted: 11 July,all,Jiang,"Deserts of Kharak boasts a fascinating story, wonderful atmosphere, and entertaining and varied campaign, but it's deeply marred by its lack of replayability, awkwardly fast gameplay, and relatively short campaign. Multiplayer is finicky enough that it can be difficult to get a game going, and the AI is a bit clunky and easy to overcome.All in all, it's worth a shot if you love Homeworld and want a prequel to the first game. However, its low replayability and utter lack of any new singleplayer content make this a title I'd recommend against purchasing. If you see it on sale for 50% or better off, then it's worthwhile. Otherwise, I'd suggest spending your dollarydoos elsewhere."
