76561198046960736,Not Recommended,281610,20652010,"Posted: 20 January, 2016",all,FewFingerDeathPunch,"This will be my final write up on this review, as I have now completed the campaign and because of that alone my opinion is now a very, VERY cautious recommendation IF all you are after is the prequel story in a rushed format. If you're after replayability, hours of skirmishing etc, then go play Homeworld Remastered/ClassicsI've played the Classics since I was a kid back on a 98 os system (all the way through xp and windows 7, I've probably put over a 1000 hours into each) and I've put well over a 100 hours into remastered just so you know that this is an opinion on the game from someone who has been tainted with the previous Homeworlds. A new fans opinion may obviously vary from mine.I'll start off with the positive:The art style of the cutscenes is fantastic, it's actually something I wish other media would uptake it's so pretty.The music is classic Homeworld, desperate and dramatic tones of orchestra, it's great.There's more dynamic battlechatter (for example when an enemy is detected but not seen units will report they have signals but no visual conformation) which is a very nice touchGuard formations are back, (took us this long to get that back?)Atmosphere and story is very homeworld, a desperate struggle against a formiddable enemyLove the fact Rachel is a unit, any game which lets you some way have a badass chick is usually good in my booksArtifact recovery is a fun little thing to do, and it's a great asset, they offer great strengthening factors to your fleetThe prequel story is very compelling, not to spoil anything but after the end of this I immediately went and started playing Homeworld 1 againNow the negative:The game looks like♥♥♥♥♥♥when compared to remastered, even on ultra, ship textures are okay and the explosions are....okay, but the other FX look pretty poor and the sand textures look extremely lat and lifeless, to the point where I look at the screenshots above and scoff.Combat has a serious lack of individual unit importance, the only way you can win is mostly by unit spam, you'll throw a lot of the starting units straight to the windsThere's no ballistics, at least from what I can tell, rail gun hits seem to be RNG and everything else is just falsely animated when compared to what's actually shooting and what's actually taking damageNo docking? No harvester drop off animations? What?TERRIBLE unit clipping, like half the stuff on the surface doesn't actually exist, I've got scavengers just driving through the wreck of the Kalash like it's nobodies businessVery little unit variation both in each race and between the two races, one race hovers and the other doesn't but in terms of combat they are identicalOnly 5 maps for Skirmish/OnlineThe controls are pretty butchered, unnecessary button changes to a system that was well understood and well loved, and you can't even get that system back because the controls are NOT-REBINDABLENo ALT focusing, making trying to keep an eye on your units in combat even more difficult without them clipping through sand, mountains, bigger units and resourcesUnit target priority is very odd, rail guns will try to shoot tiny fast LAV's while another railgun is killing them, it's like they just defend themselves from what they see first which will ALWAYS be the LAV'sI know this is precise but, the support carriers guns will all fire when in combat, even if not all of them are on target, so you get bullets just flying off the thing in random directions for no reasonMissiles and bombs have very random velocities, they'll launch/drop at reasonable speeds but as soon as they get close to a target they'll accelerate to ridiculous speeds and perform seriously unbelieveable changes in direction. I understand a bit of smudging to make stuff like that hit but, this is immersion breakingI find very few of the scenarious in the campaign to be imaginative, you've got your standard first mission of testing resourcing, production and the like and from there's it's just been engage and destroy the enemy mostly (as well as the aforementioned artifacts to recover)Skirmish AI is both useless and a dirty cheater at harvesting resources much faster than you ever couldCamera gets stuck at certain zooms sometimesSometimes turret animations will simply fail and rounds will come out the back of them instead of through the barrelOf course some of this can be fixed in patches, we NEED Alt focusing again and we DEFINITELY need rebindable controls, as well as a fix for the buggy clipping, certain odd unit behaviour and some busted animationsMy final word is that I really want to say I enjoyed this, hell I probably did, the campaign (as un-imaginative as it is) is enough to make you want to complete it, but that's pretty much all you're getting. If you're a die-hard Homeworld fan and you want to experience this epic journey of the great expedition then be prepared to experience the feeling of a very rushed game along with it. Buggy animations, unit clipping, fairly certain I've mentioned it all. And it will ruin the immersive moments, even the end of the game was almost ruined for me, as the final scene plays and the beautiful animation style shows us the sky of Kharak, Rachel was saying her piece and was interrupted twice by the blockhead Intel Officer saying ""Galsien fighters approaching"" even after I'd killed every single last one of them.I just chose to ignore him (the ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥)"
76561198033025849,Recommended,281610,20647096,"Posted: 20 January, 2016",all,Vikare,"L I T E R A L L Y  H O M E W O R L D.RTS vehicle physics look better than my lifeHomeworld has always been a game that's very intense with the art direction, so the world looks absolutely flawless, though perhaps it might not be for some. All of the cutscenes thus far have been fantastic with their animated art concept. The actual gameplay is very similar to Homeworld, but now instead of a groundbreaking 3D space RTS... we're on a planet. Blackbird made sure to try new things here though, and they want to keep some aspects of the original game alive in that now the game feels quite authentic. The terrain isn't flat, you have topographical maps and need to pick and choose the best positions to place your forces if you want the advantage you desire. The storyline is top notch."
,Recommended,281610,26746740,"Posted: 22 November, 2016",all,Kacebus,"Full disclosure: I'm one of those people... a 90's PC gamer that was blown away by the first Homeworld. It's been propped up in my mind as one of the greatest strategy games of all time. I've gone back and played it ad nauseum... yadda yadda yadda. I'm one of those types.People like me will tell you that Deserts of Kharak has mighty big shoes to fill. And... It doesn't quite live up to it. How could it? Homeworld is more or less an 'ideal' at this point. But I'll also tell you in the same breath that Kharak is a game worth playing. The art is stylish. The graphics retain that sense of scale that made the original so impressive. The story is decent; more about representing a sense of place than of character development (very sci fi). Most importantly, it feels like a Homeworld game.Like I said though, it falls short. The game is over much too quickly, and the pacing is inconsistent. Kharak is a road trip game, but its jerky flow makes it seem like you're missing out of huge swaths of the game's story.The gameplay is flashy and nice. The vehicles are awesome but you'll find yourself falling into a successful routine and ignoring the game mechanics that are introduced later in-game. There's just not enough space to breathe and explore these new styles of play. Kharak lacks the replay value of the previous games.While I honestly can't see myself revisiting the game on it's current merits, I feel Blackbird took a step in the right direction. It ain't a retread. Ground-based combat was refreshing. It opens up new avenues in the future.Luckily for us Homeworld fans, Deserts of Kharak sold well enough. That's the takeaway for me. The game is a servicable successor, but most importantly, I haven't been more excited about the future of the franchise in a very long time."
