76561198005406191,Recommended,281610,32118960,Posted: 1 June,all,servvsumbrarum,"Greetings, as always!  The Homeworld franchise is one of my favorite settings and the RTS design it is based off stands as one the great pillars of the genre.  As a whole it holds a solid third place for me in the RTS world (followed by StarCraft & Dawn of War) and constantly fights with Command & Conquer (mainly out of nostalgia) for that spot.Art in Motion:  This game is beautiful to watch, at first you may think ‘it’s a desert, not much to look at’ but every part of the game is driven to amazing detail from the way the vehicles move over the sand, even ramping it with realistic physics to the way the weapons fire causing displaced particles and even looking at the scale of the vehicles themselves this game is awe inspiring.  The music, sound effect and even the contestant banter of the units themselves complete this immersion.  I found myself constantly zooming in to look at the units closely and to listen to their communications among each other.  They talked about nearby threats, heat levels or even how to most efficiently to dismantle that structure.  Movement is amazing, the game takes every movement in consideration, and your battlecruisers have to take time to turn around where your hover units just start moving backwards and slowly rotate.  There is the occasional physics goof where a vehicle pops up from a shot or a hill and flips but it is more amusing than an actual problem.Riding before you know it:  Let me start by saying the tutorial is amazing, it explains everything in an understandable way and the game’s already amazing controls always allows you to fully understand what is going on and allows you to make the decisions needed to succeed.  I never felt like the game was fighting me; anytime something didn’t happen fast enough it was a limitation of the unit, something measurable that I was well of, something that I could anticipate at a later battle.  In addition to the effectiveness of the controls the units themselves are all useful depending on how you play.  It is possible to bulldoze an enemy with cruisers and there is little that your light attack vehicles can do to stop them.  But while they are slowly trotting towards your carrier your LAVs snuck behind and completely destroyed your long range railguns, and their salvagers.  Every tool has a purpose and exploiting your opponents’ weakness with them is what makes the game engaging.What’s the Next Step:  So what’s bad?  Well, some of the physics can be odd (like I said above) but more annoyingly sometimes the secondary objectives don’t complete or un-complete upon loading a saved game.  Sometimes the audio cuts out randomly during cutscenes and missions tend to drag on terribly at the end while you are cleaning up resources and artifacts.  But to be honest, this can all be forgiven as this game is outstanding overall.  I am honestly completely happy with this game aside that I would always like to see more.I never thought that the desert could be interesting but this game does amazing work towards the environment.  This is one of my favorite games of all-time and any fan of RTS gaming has most likely already played this.  If you are new or haven’t please do, you won’t be disappointed.   This is an RTS done right, this is mobile base building done right, this is just plainly a game done right.  Now, give me more!  Oh, every RTS needs a sensor pane like Homeworld, please do."
