,Recommended,281610,20654595,"Posted: 20 January, 2016",all,Tergeron,"If you're in any way a fan of the Homeworld series, this game will carry with it almost all of the things you loved from previous games. It's not in a 3d space, but it carries over the art style, music, design and interface.Difficulty wasn't a cake walk, but I still managed to beat the game within 9 hours. Compared to say Homeworld which required you to accumulate large amounts of units and cheese the global supply limit by salvage, and say Homeworld 2 where you could very methodicly engage a portion of the map, mine, and rebuild before going to the next mission, HW:DoK fits somewhere inbetween and I find this to be refreshing, as I was always producing units and was never given the chance to simply max my fleet out before moving on.On that note unit production is different in that for one faction in the game all of your units are produced from your ""mothership"" with numerous production queue's. As far as I know, there is no limit to any one unit type but rather there is simply a global supply limit and you can work in any units you wish within this limit. Research seems to provide you with numerous options that exceede the amount of resources you can obtain, so researching feels more like a choice than in previous games within the series.I could describe a lot more to the game, but I find the differences to be refreshing while still feeling like a Homeworld game even without space and my beloved ion frigates. If you're a fan of Homeworld pick this up, and if you aren't but love RTS games, I'd give this game a shot. If you like this, try out the older Homeworld games and prepare to sit with the rest of us waiting for Homeworld 3."
,Recommended,281610,20653917,"Posted: 20 January, 2016",all,Kimsemus,"Homeworld: Deserts of Kharak is a true continuation of Homeworld gameplay, even if the story takes place far before the events of Homeworld 1.Many Homeworld veterans might be concerned that battles take place on land instead of in space, however all the pieces are still there:The Mothership/Flagship is now replaced by a massive central crawler that serves the same functions. You produce ""capital"" crawlers in the same vein as capital ships in previous titles, and use a mix of light and medium units in the same vein as Fighters/Corvettes/Frigates.Positioning is still ""3D"" in the sense that using proper elevation can yield significant bonuses in combat, and epxanding your sensor net and keeping intel on the enemy, as in previous titles, is key. If anything, I find the gameplay more enjoyable than even Homeworld 2, as combat is accessible, properly paced, and still leaves ample room for tactics and positioning.Graphic and sound design is SUPERB. There are FEW RTS titles that capture the atmosphere quite like this game does. Lighting and specular design is amazing, the desert maps are incredibly detailed and somehow still offer plenty of visual variety. Units are highly detailed and the wreckage and scorched earth of an engagement are satisfying. The unit chatter and tiny details in audio design only add to the effect.This is a superb evolution of the homeworld series and the RTS genre. I cannot wait for Workshop support and see what else the developer does with this game."
,Recommended,281610,22368796,"Posted: 11 April, 2016",all,stimpy77,"Well, here it is, the prequel to Homeworld. This game didn't start out as a Kharak story; it started out as just a new RTS game by Blackbird Interactive which consisted largely of the original Homeworld team. When the Homeworld franchise was auctioned off (again) by Gearbox, Gearbox tracked down Blackbird Interactive and partnered up with them to get their RTS game reconstructed to be a Homeworld prequel. It took all of a year or two to rewrite the storyline and plot and apply narration (etc) assets for it.The good:Beautiful game matching the aesthetics overall of Homeworld.Brillliant artwork, graphics, music, sound, narriation/acting.Gameplay mechanics very similar to Homeworld.Fun mechanics, very playable and fun game.[Barely] satisfying campaign length. (Could be longer, feels rushed, but generally satisfying-ish.)The bad:No true 3D gameplay (but definitely 3D terrain if that matters, along the lines of Starcraft)Infuriating glitches such as aircraft needing to be double-clicked (while they're moving in flight, good luck) and ""reminded"" to land and rearm.Auto-save checkpoints immediately precede long cutscenes that can't be skipped; you must remember to save after every cutscene if you don't want to repeat them.Plot and game ending triggers block resource collection for building up for next mission.Massive narrative plothole at ending requires a complete understanding of the first level of Homeworld 1 before can it be understood to say nothing of being appreciated.Conclusion:I have mixed feelings about this game. Overall, it's a good game, generally satisfying for the Homeworld fan, as the essential gameplay elements that made Homeworld great (other than total 3D strategy) are here. If you're a Homeworld fan, there's not enough to hate here to avoid it. You'll like it."
