76561198031710497,Recommended,281610,29271572,Posted: 15 January,all,Alpacachino,"Disclaimer: I never intended to play multiplayer in this game. This review is solely based on the single player campaign.Homeworld: Deserts of Kharak is set on, you guessed it, the planet of Kharak, and is a prequel the the now classic Homeworld games. Instead of the sometimes too-complex-for-it's-own-good-3D-plane battlefields of Homeworld 1 and 2, Deserts of Kharak plays a lot more like a traditional kind of RTS, seeing as all the fighting takes place on the surface of the planet. Despite this pretty big change, it still manages to capture the essence of those great past games, with good looking animations and unit models.The story is actually pretty decent for an RTS. Centered around this lady scientist (Rachel something?) and her search for her brother in the midst of a war, it manages to hit a nice balance between a war story, and a personal narative.I really liked my time with the game, even if it was ""only"" the singleplayer. I got the game from a steam sale for around €16, which is a no brainer in my opinion."
,Recommended,281610,20840147,"Posted: 29 January, 2016",all,allquixotic,"The aesthetic and design of Kharak is so interesting and so unique that I really find this a compelling RTS. The storyline is the best I've seen in an RTS in a very long time; this game is (or should be) all about the single player campaign. The multiplayer is fairly standard.The thing that keeps me so intrigued by this game is the ""land carrier"" concept. The way it's presented, the way they show the lives of the crew and the struggle they have to go through to keep things together, reminds me a lot of the new Battlestar Galactica in its concept. I've always been a fan of huge ships going on an epic journey, weathering direct fire and scrambling fighters; this game gives you the unique ground equivalent of BSG, more or less.For anyone who enjoyed Homeworld OR Battlestar Galactica and enjoys a heavily story-driven single-player campaign, with a small amount of fun to be had with multiplayer (maybe more than a little fun if you play it with friends), I can HIGHLY recommend this game. The mechanics are tight, there aren't any serious bugs, the music is awesome, the sound effects are satisfying, and the general concept of ""I'm commanding a massive land carrier that's a mobile city"" is just so... AWESOME... that I'm excited to recommend this game as one of the few games that has truly given me joy in the past few years.The team who created this game should also kindly shut up and take my money for Homeworld 3 and begin development right away (if they haven't already). This is exactly the team of artists, writers and developers -- the exact people who made this game -- that we sorely need to stick together to make the NEXT epic Homeworld game. Do it. Do it now."
