76561197977262110,Recommended,281610,20719167,"Posted: 23 January, 2016",all,kazabomber,"Since I haven't played enough multiplayer to really comment on multiplayer balancing, this would mainly be a review for single player campaign.The campaign itself is wonderfully done with the right combination of story and visual story telling. Story is being told actively as you play the game, and the pace at which the game unfolds new features in the campaign allows the player to pick up what to do with different units very naturally. Story integrates itself well to the original Homeworld universe, and suble hints suggest that this conflict behind the Desert of Kharak campaign does not invole any clear ""villain"" or the ""good-guy"", but a society torn between progressivist and conservative at a time of hardship on a planet going through major climate change. If you require the story to be told in your face with everything blatantly obvious, you would probably not enjoy the story of Desert of Kharak. However, if you enjoy picking up subtle hints and plot pieces spread throughout the game's campaign, you'll enjoy playing through this game.As for the aesthetics and presentation of the game, it inherits a lot of the visual and atomospher of the original Homeworld series. The designs are very minimal yet cleanly done, and if you were a fan of the original series (or a fan of the more realistic Scifi design), it'll most likely please you. Voice acting is also done in a natural manner instead of the over-the-top method you would find in lot of the other games. However, this is not without it's cons. Although the game put heavy emphasis on terrain utilization, it's sometimes difficult to visually decipher which grounds offer to terrain advantage until your units are physically interacting with the terrain. Since the difficulty level of the campaign is not too high this is not a major set back, but I wonder if this issue would be addressed in the future patch.Overall, the game offer a lot of promise, and I'm sure a lot of the kinks would be worked out in the near future. I highly recommend this game to the fans of the original Homeworld series as well as fans of RTS. Those who enjoyed games like Total Annihilation or Supreme Commander would definitely enjoy this game."
