,Recommended,281610,29170621,Posted: 10 January,all,GarrickWinter,"While this is a prequel to the Homeworld games, I decided to play this first, and I was never lost or feeling left out. Even if this would be your first Homeworld game, go ahead and give it a shot!Deserts of Kharak is a game with very interesting pacing. Units turn and move quite slowly overall, and many ranged attacks take a while to land, but a combination of strong counters and powerful area of effect weapons means that once a battle starts it's often over very quickly, one way or another. The significant impact of terrain elevation on damage and your units' ability to see their targets is very easy to overlook, but beware: it really matters.Sometimes this all means one or two wrong choices will cripple your entire operation in seconds, but on the plus side you also have time to break off attacks, and your decisions really do matter - going into the same fight with a different mix of units and tactics can make a dramatic difference.The story is compelling if simple, and has a great mystical undertone that reminds me of Battlestar Galactica. The game is also beautiful - seriously, I don't think video game deserts have ever looked this good. Weapons fire satisfyingly, weather and sand effects are convincing, and the architectural and vehicle style is cohesive and immersive. The units are a bit visually indistinct at playable distances, but if you're managing hotkey groups actively it shouldn't be such a big deal.My main complaint with the game is the way it handles zooming and the visual (small-scale, pretty) versus tactical (large-scale, abstract) maps. Rather than smoothly transitioning between the two, there's a key transition, and moving from the tactical to the visual map often results in the camera ending up somewhere in the middle of nowhere. Double-clicking zooms you from the tactical map to a specific spot on the visual map, unless you’re double-clicking on a unit, but the camera angles often end up skewed away from whatever you had set it to before, and the camera is often zoomed too close to the ground as well.Oh, and couldn't the Escape key bring up the damned menu? You'd think.Aside from some interface frustrations, though, this is a great RTS game, suitably challenging and with great aesthetic and style. I highly recommend everyone interested try it out."
,Recommended,281610,29175003,Posted: 10 January,all,sharpshooter1776,"This game was great.Really story driven, and overall a great RTS... minor complaint for only 2 factions. But overall great story and gameplay."
