76561197972287768,Recommended,281610,28368913,"Posted: 14 December, 2016",all,Drunkenkitten,"Not a perfect game by any means, but pretty enough looking and sounding to add a sort of aesthetic enjoyment in playing, and the strategy genre is few and far between nowadays. The music, artwork and scenery are genuinly enjoyable, and the story is passable enough to string it all together. The campaign is fairly short, but to be honest if you're like me and don't have too long to sink into a game its a decent enough length.Its hard to describe why I wouldn't call this game great, despite it having hints of greatness. The camera can be hard to get just right - its always close enough to work, but never quite comfortable. I often wanted to zoom out slightly more than allowed, meaning I spent half the game in the strategic overview map view, clicking on little icons when I really wanted to be seeing the action in all its visual glory. Theres no mini map, so you will often find yourself feeling slightly out of the loop.I haven't delved into the multiplayer too much yet, but after a couple of skirmishes the mechanics strike me as averagely good for online play - its the sort of thing I imagine playing with some friends a few times then dropping, as opposed to getting competitive like company of heroes or one of the other big strategy titles.Overall - 7/10, pick up on sale and enjoy, and try to enjoy the atmosphere throughout the relatively short ride."
76561197960531444,Recommended,281610,29767185,Posted: 7 February,all,Spiffguru,"Deserts of Kharak has most of the elements that make a great sci-fi RTS, but it comes together a bit clumsily in the end-- especially where UI and controls are concerned-- so that it's harder to play than it need be, and harder to recommend than it should be. As a long-time Homeworld fan I was pleasantly surprised at how well Deserts translates some of the aesthetic and design of previous games to a ground-based game. Deserts has great visuals and exciting sound worthy of the franchise. Unfortunately, the game is bogged down by a clunky hotkey system in comparison to previous Homeworld titles so that it can be hard to find and control units easily. Though the build menu allows you to create a queue, the research menu does not, and you can only access this by selecting the mothership (rather than just pressing 'r'). Altogether, there's a lot to like here, but it lacks the refinement that has given games like the original Homeworld its staying power as an RTS."
