,Not Recommended,281610,30479852,Posted: 12 March,all,RoBorg,"Before anything: this isn't a bad game. It's just... not good enough.I actually enjoyed playing through its campaign, but sadly I never really felt the homeworld feeling of the firts two chapters.Drawings are still cool. But that's it.To be more precise, two kind of player will play this game:- those who played Homeworld and/or Homeworld 2- those who didn'tClever, am I not?---------------Anyway, for the latter it's simple: it's not a RTS that you might like, played out of the blue, with no memories about the first two chapters. The few things the plot shows are just as empty as a wall paint plot evolution drying up, if you don't know what those things will become in the future (aka Homeworld 1).---------------For the former... eh.What made great Homeworld 1/2?Pathos, empathy, tactics, epicness. All in a strategic game in an era where only a coulpe of RTS could claim this much.Let's see some of the reasons, with their counterpart in DoK.---------------- That feeling of sad pride. The sacrifice of the Bentusi. That ""The Mothership must survive"" just before the hyperjump. ==> NOTHING relevant happens in DoK. It sould be a prequel. In fact is just as deep as ONE of the story drawings of HW1.- 3D battles, with absolute control over the fleet formation, the attack angles, flanking moves, scouting the void, hiding in nebulas, etc.==> Deserts of Kharak it's a 2D flat map. Some obstacles here and there. No tactical choices. Nearly fixed paths. Paradoxically, the 3D nearly empty maps of HW1/2 felt more elaborated and rich of opportunities.- Impressive number of ways to battle. Bait enemies. Or draw fire and go bomber.  Or Frigate rolling stone, protected by Fighters. Or battlecruisers blast and hyperjump off. Or kamikaze-probes =)==> Assault units vs Railgun, Armored vs Assault, Railgun vs Armored. Stop. Then you get battlecruisers. At that poin sell every small unit aside antiaerial and go battlecruisers: they can rush through the entire campaign by simple autoattack movement.- The option to destroy the subsystems of a capital ship to cripple it before finishing it was a master's touch in the creation of HW2.==> Removed. No subsystems. And I don't mean that ""you can't destroy them"". You cannot even build them. It's all just research. Mandatory research.- Hyperspace tactical jumps. No explainations needed.==> No Hyperspace jumps at all. No explainations needed. And it would be acceptable: I mean, the hyperpace jumps are not jet discovered. But at least some form of tactical movements. Air carriers for quick movement. Something...- An assorted fleet with a spot for every. single. unit. Even the simplest explorer or the Fighter had a solid role in the tactics.==> You get to build the battleships? You can forget of the small veicles. Only keep the ones for antiaerial defense. Go battleships and trample everything.- Capturing. This was one of the pillars of the whole game in Homeworld 1. Still great in Homeworld 2.==> Capturing is just a side effect if a skill that says ""immediately destroy one enemy unit"". Also bad AI that keeps firing to the captured unit, often blasting it apart, while it's being driven to the Carrier for conversion.- Speaking of losses you had to build an assorted fleed, manage it cleverly, and never, ever, let something bigger than a corvette be destroyed. You needed to deploy your best tactics most of the time.==> The final, big, decisive battle? Select your fleet and send it in autoattack in the approximative direction of the target. Done. Thanks. Goodbye. The previuos battles? Select your army and send it in the direction of the objective. You have plenty of resources to win the campaign with that, and plenty of army slots to trample everything with just marginal losses fully refillable.- The immense satisfaction of starting each mission with an undersized army if compared to the enemy, and win by raw tactics and strategy.==> I have NEVER seen more than 3-4 enemy cruisers in the same screen, in DoK. My fleet had 26 of them. And anything smaller got shredded by artillery way before getting in range.- Split your forces. Protect the collectors. Attack the objective. Send units to escort the ally. All while protecting the Mothership!==> Just move your entire fleet, Carrier included along the path, and harvest resources as you pass by them. Also no need to protect the Carrier: it can fend off any attack in normal difficulty with no help from anything. So use fleet to attack, and Carrier / Support Cruiser to harvest.- Research tree. Nothing new even in HW1/2, ok, but still gave the player the chance to define the fleet priorities.==> In DoK might as well remove it. Most upgrade are mandatory story driven. Those who aren't you have plenty of time and resources to research them. And half of them just unlocks in the last 2 missions. When you don't really need anything more to win (in my playthrough the enemy Carrier - the objective of the mission - drifted from its path lured by accident by a collector, got close to my cruisers, and got blasted while I was happily micromanaging the mine-laying-duty on the other side of the fleet).------------------------------Final verdict: I had great hopes. But if you really want to feel the Homeworld you love, just play HW1/2. And if you have never player HW before, play HW1/2. Non-remastered version. Remastered version is still story-beautiful, but the game itsel is somehow way easier.One ""could-have-been-good"" point: gathering artifacts for powering up the Carrier was a good idea, but largely underdeveloped, sadly.As a note: I played the whole campaign in normal difficulty. Some critics regarding ""how hard the game is not"" might not be valid in hard difficulty. This I do not know.Still, if I compare this normal difficulty to HW1/2 normal difficulty, the gap is huge. DoK is really, really too easy."
