76561198023995376,Not Recommended,281610,27841048,"Posted: 27 November, 2016",all,StranaMechty,"I wanted to like Deserts of Kharak, I truly did. It represents the first truly new thing for the Homeworld franchise in over a decade. As a hardcore fan of the first two games who plasters the Hiigaran insignia over everything, real or virtual, and can recite all the cinematics from memory, I *really* wanted to like this game. But I can't.A mediocre RTS that manages to have more bugs and fewer features than its now-teenaged predecessors (no formations, no stances, shadows are a mess, etc.). Its very existence depends on a retcon of existing canon (the extensive historical and technical briefing book originally released with Homeworld 1 states categorically that no major conflicts occurred for centuries prior to Homeworld 1, the version of this book printed by Gearbox in the re-issue changes this fact to allow for Deserts of Kharak to exist) and it goes out of its way to twist that canon like a pretzel (spoiler warning: you'd think someone would've mentioned the giant orbital death ray left behind and been less surprised when the people who placed it showed up again). Furthermore, it couldn't even make its surprise twist surprising, and somehow manages to look worse than the Homeworld: Remastered games that came out *before* this did.For existing Homeworld fans: Look elsewhere, this is just a worse version of what we've already got that takes dumb liberties with the story.For those who've never played Homeworld: Look elsewhere (might I suggest Homeworld?), there are better RTS games out there (like Homeworld)."
