,Recommended,281610,28285476,"Posted: 10 December, 2016",all,Terr,"I think whether you like Deserts of Kharak will depend on which parts of the previous Homeworld games you like. If you enjoy the story, art, sound, aesthetics, missions, and basic combat, then grab it on sale and you'll be quite satisfied.If you enjoy careful tactical choices, then you'll be a little disappointed. While there are some new  tactical tools in the dunes -- new to the Homeworld series, anyway --  your fleet will be simpler, and your ability to direct your units is cruder. I'm no RTS expert, but in the singleplayer campaign I often ended up resigned to controlling a ""big slow blob of death"", due to the difficulty of micromanaging and the lack of formations.The single-player campaign on Medium difficulty took about 10 hours, which to a certain extent may represent a less attrition-based pacing.Pro:* Has all the right Homeworld looks.* Has all the right Homeworld sounds.* Units have cover and indirect fire.* Height advantage when firing on lower enemies.* Smoke screens.* Centralized control of air units seems odd at first, but it works.* Powerful veterancy bonuses.Cons:* No more ability to pause and issue orders in solo campaign.* No formations: Difficult to prevent fast units from staying with slower ones without micromanagement or ordering them to ""guard"" the slowest unit.* Key-combinations are less expansive and cannot be re-bound.* No more unit engagement rules (chase vs guard).* No more unit tactics (trading speed for firepower).* Your land-carrier is your only production unit.* Some unskippable mission cutscenes* Unit icons/portraits could be more distinctive from one-another."
