76561197990782887,Recommended,281610,28940094,Posted: 2 January,all,Teric,"As a long-time fan of the original Homeworld, I was eager to try out this new title.  The series has always been heavy on deep storytelling, intense combat, careful resource management, and critical tactical decisions; these are what kept me coming back to play Homeworld again and again.DoK did not disappoint me at all.  In fact, after finishing the single player campaign, I found myself wishing the story would continue over additional missions.  Like HW, I found myself carefully trying to keep my units alive from mission to mission, especially now with the promotion system that gives veteran units significant bonuses.  I did my best to mine out all possible resources from each map before continuing on, in order to maximize research and be able to build up my army.I ran into the unit cap fairly quickly, and I found that this was an interesting departure from the original.  There was a point during the campaign where I was running around with 7000+ RU and 15000+ CU without anything to spend them on.  However, as more research opened up and my unit cap increased, that surplus quickly depleted and I found myself having to make criticial decisions about which research channels to persue or sideline.  It makes me wonder how the original HW would have been different if there had been a unit cap.The story of DoK did not disappoint either--it was fascinating and delightful to see the actions and history of Rachel S'Jet before she gave herself to be the central fleet command of the mother ship in HW.For those who enjoy a story-rich RTS that isn't a mindless 'Build-And-Battle' slug-fest, Deserts of Kharak is the game for you."
