,Recommended,281610,28957919,Posted: 2 January,all,madbop,"The story's pace is very similar to Homeworld, but it is really a shame that the game speed cannot be reduced. Due to the tremendous speed one only views the map in the abstract sensor mode.I really miss the hold-mode where actions could be strategically coreographed and timed - and as another reviewer mentioned already - there was time to view the really nice graphics - I was hoping that the famous HW-formations and defensive patterns would have made it to the sibling, but unfortunately this was lost in this 3D to 2D-translation of HW.It is also painful that the real-world view is only very limited in its zoom capabilities and that there is no way to view the regions one acts within the sensor manager are also displayed as real world cut-outs - this IMHO would deepen the immersion into the game. What I also miss in respect to HW is the 3D ability and I would have expected that the environment in a modern desert game would interact much more with the gamer's fleet - in one way by influencing the speed, detection range and vision, on the other by being alterable by explosives etc. - This really is a missed opportunity.Also some of the designs look like they have been hastely copied from an oldsmobile paintbook. I mean a giant hover-airgraft carrier that has a front like an ancient car? really? - And what is quite annoing is the lack of mass in the game. Why does the Hover carrier jump like a ping-pong-ball even in the cut-scenes. Is physics really such a nasty thing to control nowadays? - also some crashes of fighter aircraft could profit from a modern physics engine that lets vesselss fall apart and dunes collapse or move with the wind.Also the scripting, balancing and AI is sometimes a bit of an annoyance. - Is it really necessary to build inifinite spawn points into the missions? Wouldn't there be other events that could build a more realistic pressure?I also would have liked some kind of automatisation support for the player - e.g. when to pull back or when to advance - this micromanagement always is painful and the lack of the in-game-stop-time (which is different to a pause-function) that makes HW such a teriffic experience does not make it any easier.All in all it is an enjoyable game that is worth to buy and play (although I think that 40+ pricing is a little bit off for any game that is sold under a 1person no-resell STEAM license), which unfortunately suffers from a few minor but annoying bugs, with an interesting story, but full of missed opportunities to take the core idea of the game one step into a new century (or millennium?).I really hope that this series could get a successor that combines this great but old framework and infuses it with something new an modern than a statically scripted series of events that also makes the world more alive, the sand hot and deadly, the wind painful and the dust a means to hide away from an overwhelmingly powerful enemy, where tactics and strategy helps to turn the tides, rather than large numbers of battleships and high-click rates of classic scissors/paper combinations of war machines."
