76561198007090818,Not Recommended,281610,29249909,Posted: 14 January,all,brynethp,"So close, but some significant annoyances mean that I can't quite bring myself to recommend this.  For the sale price I paid (<£10), I don't regret my purchase, but I'd be upset if I’d paid full price.Starting with the positives, the visuals (units and landscapes), and particularly the sound design are fantastic.  The storyline is good, the missions are varied and well made.  What lets it down is the underlying game, the mechanics.No formations, very poor unit AI, the fact that a mixed group of units given a move order will proceed at their individual top speeds, spreading out and leaving themselves vulnerable.  The bizarre decision to put a cooldown on (for example) the salvagers demolition charge, which means that I can queue up four of them if I’m out of range of the target, but if I’m next to it I have to wait – why?  An Inelegant hack to allow hotkey modification I know is a limitation of the engine used (Unity), but still feels shoddy.  This is a slightly faster moving game than the first two, so the removal of the ability to issue orders while paused is deeply annoying.  I've been an RTS fan since the days off Dune II, Warcraft and TA and it’s enormously frustrating to see UI design that mostly ignores the lessons of the last 25 years.This game is currently the same price as the Homeworld remastered collection, which offers two superior games.  If you haven’t played a Homeworld game before, buy that.  If you’re already a fan, it might be worth picking this one up in a sale."
