76561197991896786,Recommended,281610,20761398,"Posted: 25 January, 2016",all,Crowe,"TLDR;-Worth the price tag-Could have been a bit more polished-Not much content (Only a few multiplayer maps)-Solid game overallNot going to lie, the AI is dumb, the campaign is very easy. I chose normal difficulty on my first playthrough, and never even came close to losing a mission. On my second playthrough, I chose the harder 'classic' difficulty, and only lost once, (Due to my own stupidity, not the difficulty of the mission).The storyline is nice, although the campaign feels quite short, and ends on a rather dull note, in my opinion at least. And from the outset, you are told the objective in the desert will lead to the salvation of the Kushun people, but why? How do they know this? Just seems like strange dialogue to have so early in the game when they aren't even sure what they are going to find out there in the desert.I found the campaign to be nicely immersive however, and it seems a lot of thought and development has gone into the technology and engineering of the units, for how a civilization living on a desert planet would design their vehicles and such.The camera is somewhat annoying as well, much of the time I found it very claustrophobic outside of the sensors manager (The blue map you get when you hit spacebar), and there isn't a lot of range to zoom in and out, it is capped at a very low altitude. Unit selection is kind of a pain too, there is no military-priority selection, so dragging a big box around everything is only going to select everything.Pathfinding AI is quite bad too, on my second playthrough I tried building a lot of cruisers to form a carrier battlegroup, but most of them wouldn't follow my carrier properly, and would sit still trying to engage an enemy unit that wasn't within their line of sight.There are no formation controls as far as I can see, and no proper positioning for units in formations, when told to guard/escort your carrier, all the utility units place themselves on the outside of the formation (where they will get killed by the first unit that attacks you), instead of hugging close to the carrier like you would expect.There isn't a lot of content either, I seem to remember there being a much bigger variety of units in the other HW games, in this game you have;A resource collectorLight attack vehicle (Scissors)Armoured Assault Vehicle (Rock)Railgun (Paper)Baserunner (minelayer)4 x kinds of cruisersA fighterA bomberThat is it, so overall it is a very simple game, there aren't different kinds of frigates or corvettes like we had in the other games. But this is partially compensated for by your carrier (mothership) which can shunt power and be used offensively, defensively, or as a support ship.There are only 5 multiplayer maps too, which is a shame because it could really use the variety. I am presuming they will bring out more DLC to rectify this (Which we will have to pay for).But overall, I am happy with my purchase, if you like homeworld, you will probably like this. If you aren't familiar with homeworld, I would probably just stick with the remastered collection, at least acquiant yourself with it before buying this one, because the story of this game really depends on your knowledge of the other games."
