,Not Recommended,281610,20648720,"Posted: 20 January, 2016",all,Gimboid,"I've clocked a little over an hour into the game and completed the first three (of what I believe is around 10-12 missions for the story) and have stopped for now to provide a review and feedback.My initial reaction to playing the game, is that there are some deep seeded homeworld aspects that are missing from the game, this was something I was expecting due to the limited press demo's provided prior to the games release.Homeworld as a series remains my all-time favourite, I am an owner of the Remastered Collectors Edition and have dumped quite a few hours into that now that I can play homeworld on a modern PC. The negative feedback I have is such:Map Texture qualitySeems very low, I am running the game on maximum settings and the sand and scenery simply doesn't add the same atmosphere that you see in the pre-rendered footage.No Unit Interactions like Homeworld 1-2Unit interactions are a generation behind the original homeworld games. In Homeworld 1, when your resource harvester collected materials and returned to hand them in, you could actually watch it dock with your resource controller/mothership and transfer the resources back.The resource controller in DoK looks like it was going to have something similar, but they didn't finish implementing it, instead, when your resource collectors reach your collector, the mineral bar vanishes and they move off for their next collection.No DockingAnother cool and fun Sci-fi aspect of Homeworld was docking, the fact that after a run, you could dock your strike craft with your mothership or carriers for more efficient repairs (and in Catacylsm, retro-fitting), there is no docking in DoK, once your carrier spits out a new unit it outside for good, with the extremely shot repair range on the other vessels, repairing large groups of small craft is fiddly and annoying rather than engaging and fun.With your main 'mothership' in DoK being a Carrier, I was expecting the same mechanicCutscene RenderingSeveral of the cut-scenes seem a little poorly rendered, the art-style itself is fantastic, but again on a modern game on a very high-end PC, I expected more crisp visuals than how they are displaying on my PC.Zoom controlsThese seem way too limited, I find myself constantly wanting to zoom out more, the maximum limit feels very claustraphobic, resulting in an awful lot of scrolling around and quick-tabbing to the sensors manager just to view short distances, unlike again the original homeworld games where you could zoom out to a great degree for unit selection and controlsomfg, why is the main menu on F10 and not ESC like 99% of games?!?!I was taking part in a mission and needed to pause, to my surprise, ESC did nothing, I started spamming every key on the keyboard until suddenly one of them opened the game menu, I was then able to check the key-bindings (which, are fixed btw and cannot be remapped) and discover that mid-game, the main menu is accessed from F10 (whyyyyyyyyyyyyy).SummaryMaybe my expectations are too high, considering that Homeworld 1 + 2 are multi-award, ground breaking titles, but I at least, from my perspective was expecting more, not because it's a homeworld prequal, but but because it was made by the core guys that made the original HW games, I was expecting an evolution of mechanics, not a simplification that in many ways looks like a step-back to me, or, unfinished implementation due to a rushed development and launch."
