76561198035900814,Not Recommended,281610,20675953,"Posted: 22 January, 2016",all,privettk,"I'm a diehard Homeworld fan. Playing the original on Windows 98 when I was 7 got me into gaming, and since then I've played hundreds of games, yet none have matched Homeworld's place in my heart. Naturally, expectations were high for this game, perhaps unfairly so.Needless to say I was super excited to hear another Homeworld game was being made, but was equally terrified when it was announced it wouldn't be in space. Here's the impressions I've gotten so far (Mission 7, about 6 hours in)Positives:The story is great, like Homeworld stories always are.Strong voice acting - it's nice to have several people to identify with rather than just Karan S'Jet.Compelling enigmatic enemy - knowing the lore of the subsequent games makes it a lot more fun to learn about the Gaalsien.Soundtrack is classic Homeworld - almost too similar - did they actually use the same sound files?Cinematics are much improved - I loved seeing the interiors of the ""ships"" and the character's faces.Improved chatter - background chatter when things are slow really helps to build the immersion.Artifacts - although it seems to break with the HW canon, shipbreaking and collecting artifacts to beef up your ships is fun.Alas, despite all that is done well here, there are some things that at least for now have made it tough to recommend this game.Negatives:Unless you have a BRAND NEW beast of a machine, this game won't look good. I have a 4th gen i7, 8GB of RAM, and a 2GB dedicated Nvidia 745m with Windows 10, and it BARELY runs on the lowest settings. As such, my framerate is horrific, and the textures are so bad it reminds me of the 98 version of HW1. This confuses me, as I have beautiful games like Ethan Carter and HW Remastered running at 60fps on ultra. With such a laggy framerate (I'm lucky if I hit 30), immersion is instantly broken. Guess it's time to save up for yet another rig?Space is Homeworld's secret ingredient:I liked the idea of a prequel on Kharak, but space is what Homeworld does best. Watching little trucks dance around each other shooting 50 cals isn't nearly as glorious or boner-inducing as gigantic spaceships blowing the crap out of each other with big lasers. I tried so hard to like the ground fight, but the next HW project REALLY needs to head back out to space! PLEASE!Units die INCREDIBLY fast.I get it - Homeworld is designed to be a challenge by forcing you to discern the correct strategy (that's what makes it fun.) But this game punishes you like other Homeworlds never did. Your fleet will be wiped out in less than 30 seconds if you make one mistake in building your fleet. As such, you have to save OFTEN and reload those checkpoints more than I'd like.No resourcesOn one hand, I like the sense of desperation having little to no resources gives. But when my fleets are being wiped out in an instant and there are no resources left, I'm SOL and have to start again. Worse still, the old HW's had a mechanic that automatically collected any RU's left over at the end of a mission. Not the case here! Your mission will suddenly complete and your mining will be left unfinished, leaving you with nothing to rebuild next mission. While you can use a ""default"" fleet, that just feels like a cheat to me.Under constant assaultSo far, with the exception of the first mission, I have been under constant attack on multiple fronts, meaning 90% of my time is spent in the map instead of absorbing the beautiful desert world Blackbird worked so hard on building. I have no problem with coming under attack, but let me smell the desert roses a little first!I love the Homeworld universe to death and want to support this game in hopes of a HW3, but be warned - you need a beast PC to run this - and going from 3 dimensions to 2.5 will feel like a step in the wrong direction."
76561197973910616,Not Recommended,281610,21425318,"Posted: 24 February, 2016",all,jwfoxhound,This games graphics and controls are poor.  The game is very linear and quickly becomes boring.  Save your money...
