76561198001407996,Not Recommended,281610,21372646,"Posted: 21 February, 2016",all,Haurbus,"Pretense this here first, I think this is a good game, but it's not really up to the standards of todays games.We are in an era where we have a blurring number of games, and other forms of entertainment, so we have little time or money to spare on other things, and I really can't suggest Deserts of Kharak as a good option.You can feel the age of the games design in how closely it follows with Homeworld.  Very linear story, not a lot of change of scenary, relatively short campaign, no real closure at the end.Artistically it's an amazingly beautiful game.  The ship/structure designs are top notch, and the visuals and cut scenes are wonderous pieces of art, but it really feels more like an episode of a telltale game more than a fleshed out world.There is not a lot of replayability in the game despite multiplayer but few of my friends even got the game, so it heralds back to an age where massively multiplayer options were just not an option.  Lastly it feels like the difficulty ramps down slowly from the beginning then immediately near the end they dump more power than you'd ever be able to really need or want, so it steals any excitement near the crucial climax of the game.If you have nothing else you'd rather play, or spend your money on, the game is still very homeworld-esque.  Great music score, amazing visuals in mechanical design, and cut scenes, but ultimately it feels like an incomplete story, no denouement almost at all, and odd unveiling of tech progression that holds the best till last stealing a lot of the challenge from early game."
76561197970767874,Not Recommended,281610,22464998,"Posted: 16 April, 2016",all,BoB(Banglerdesh),"I am astonished at how this game is rated so highly, especially when most of those buying/playing this game, I suspect, have played homeworld 1 + 2. The is some enjoyment to be found but its short lived and just not worth the price tag or time. The are a number of major issues I have with this game.1) The game feels rushed and unfinished. For example, the appearance of some unit models doesn't fit with their final game-play implementation e.g. coalition support cruises, which function as armoured mobile resource drop of points for collectors and repair bays for all vehicles, have a large gaping whole in them where presumably collectors were supposed to dock and off-load their resources and/or where vehicles could dock for repairs. Instead resources just magically transfer from collectors to support cruises or the main carrier when the collector gets within a set range, this is similar to the coalition repairing mechanism; instead of docking, your vehicles are healed by magic beams when they are within a set range of a repair vehicle such as the support cruiser. I can understand why the developers might have changed the game-play mechanisms at a late stage; maybe they ran out of time, or it was too difficult to implement them properly, or they were causing problems/balance issues, but if so they should at least alter/re-designed the appearance of the units affected to fit with the new game-play mechanics, not doing so is just lazy.Interceptors/strike fighters for all intensive purposes play like bombers even though both factions also have dedicated bomber units as well. Each interceptor (Gaalsien) or strike fighter (Coalition) carries a single ""missile"" which it can only fire at ground targets so its essentially a small guided bomb, they do not have any other weapons and so can NOT attack other air units. I assume from their names ""interceptor"" and ""fighter"" they were originally intended to be primarily air to air fighters and likely a hard counter to bombers and gunships, instead they just work like bombers and are arguable better at bombing than the actual bombers themselves and neither faction has any aircraft capable of fighting other aircraft which just seems silly.If you order a redundant unit to be decommissioned/recycled/retired and get back a fraction of the resources used to make it, instead of returning into the carrier through the entrance (in an opposite manner to if you had just made the unit), as you would expect, the unit just clips through to the centre of the carrier from any point on the surface of the carrier which just looks stupid and breaks any immersion.2) Why can I not dock my units!? An integral and incredibly useful feature of the homeworld games was the ability to dock smaller ships with your capital ship(s). With Deserts of Kharak this feature is no more, not even the smallest of vehicles such as resource collectors can be docked. Why this feature was not included is beyond me, it would have been so useful to have been able to dock units like resource collectors and small light vehicles, to protect them during attacks such as air strikes, instead you have to micro babysit them to keep them alive, which becomes a chore and general pain in the♥♥♥♥♥ The only units that are capable of docking with the capital carrier are the aircraft, and this is only because of the way aircraft work in the game.3) The campaign is ridiculously easy (including the ""hardest"" setting) and showcases a very special A.I. You can quite easily burn through all the missions in quick succession on the ""hardest"" difficulty (classic) without a challenge; it is also relatively easy to get through the whole campaign, on classic, without loosing a single unit, albeit at a slower pace. One issue is that the computer players, both enemies and allies in the campaign, rely almost exclusively on scripted build routines, scripted patrols and scripted attacks; they have no need for resources and can see the whole map. To be fair the AI was similar in homeworld 1+2 but that is no excuse for not improving it.4) The game feels like a downgrade from Homeworld 1+2. I understand that Deserts of Kharak is suposed to be a different game, with different features and setting (on a planet/2D as opposed to in space/3D), but the developers have deliberately made the game-play extremely similar to the previous homeworld games (which is not a bad thing) so the is no logical reason not to keep in things like the ability to dock smaller vehicles which would have been an extremely useful feature as well as adding to immersion. In actual fact this game is identical gameplay wise to the original homeworld games but missing features and depth (literally); it adds nothing which is a huge shame because I feel that this game could of been very good.The campaign is very short (as with other homeworld games) and the story is ok but not great and feels fairly bland, I also get the impression that the lead up to the ending was rushed. I've come to expect and accept very generic/bland story's from games in general but because of this games predecessors I expected a bit more.The majority of my issues with the game could have fairly easily of been remedied with patches after launch but the developers instead thought it would be a ""better"" idea to re-skin a faction and sell it as DLC ><Like I have mentioned the game is not bad as such and it does have some good points, which I will now list. It looks pretty, runs relatively smoothly with only a few bugs (that I have noticed), random radio chatter (good for immersion), units are reasonably scaled.In conclusion, currently I do not recommend this game. if you have not played homeworld 1+2, buy the remastered edition of them, it is cheaper, and you get 2 games, both of which are better than this one. If you have already played homeworld 1+2 and want to play this game, I would still not recommend it, its far better to replay homeworld 1+2 and just read the plot of Deserts of Kharak on-line if you want to know the story. If you just want to play a new RTS then keep looking, the have been a few good and a lot of rubbish RTS games released recently. Personally I found Act of Aggression to be surprisingly enjoyable but I know a lot of people do not like it."
