76561197970779265,Recommended,281610,24262028,"Posted: 11 July, 2016",all,JaegerBane,"A lot of people say this is absolutely a Homeworld game... despite not being in space and set on a desert planet. Well, they're right. The music, the art, the story, the design of the units, the vast emptiness of the environments... it's all here. Do not be put off by the fact that it's set on the ground... because Blackbird Interactive definitely know what made the Homeworld games tick (and so they should - many of those guys worked on the originals) and they've served it up in spades.If you've never played a Homeworld game before, then imagine Supreme Commander set on a desert planet with Frank Herbert's Dune running on repeat in the background with your drunk mate mistaking it for Stargate every few minutes. It's that kind of scale - there are no human infantry here (your smallest unit - an attack buggy that is little more than a speck when zoomed out - is the size of a Monster Truck when considering scale to a person). This is all powered by the Unity 5 engine... and it looks spectacular. You'd think being set on a desert planet would make it look a bit samey but yikes, does this engine shine.The game itself is divided into a campaign, a skirmish, and multiplayer.The campaign is simply awesome. A prequel campaign set prior to (and covering) the discovery that kicked off the Mothership project in Homeworld 1, it's interesting to see the nods it makes to the future. I'd say it's closer to Homeworld 2 than 1, but has the same kind of themes in both - discovering the past of the Kushan, all the while fighting a war of seemingly insurmountable odds. Your 'Mothership' in this one is no colony vessel - the Kapisi is basically the USS Nimitz on tank treads and serves as a battleship, aircraft carrier, nuke platform, factory and research facility. Your fleet is persistent - units that survive one mission carry over into the next - and really makes it feel like you're running a fleet of craft just like the older Homeworld games - only you're exploring the vast desert instead of the stars. It's great.Skirmish is a bit more by the numbers. While the overall presentation and campaign is great, the actual factions are a bit dry - with only really the Gaalsien (imagine if ISIS and the Brotherhood of Nod had a lovechild and you're not far off) showing any real futuristic flair. The other base game faction - the Coalition - is about as bland as you can get (tanks, buggies, artillery, big tanks, big artillery and so on). This, mixed with patchy AI, make the skirmish a bit 'serviceable' rather than amazing. If you get the deluxe edition then you get a pair of DLC factions - Soban (Coalition who've kind of realised that they need to up their tech and use more railguns) and Kaaneph (Mad Max guys who nick their stuff from the Gaalsien). They're a bit better, but there is no deep tactical differences going on here. Everyone has rough variations of the same units.Multiplayer appears to be dead. Kaput. According to the forums there is still a small community out there, but tbh there are better RTSs if you want MP.The deluxe edition comes with the aforementioned DLC, an expedition guide (think Wikiapp with everything you ever wanted to know about Homeworld prior to the Homeworld 1) and the excellent soundtrack from the same guy who did the first two soundtracks. Personally, I got it in the Steam sale and I consider it easily worth that price... but at full price? You'd need to think about that.Regardless though... if you like sci-fi RTS, or you like Homeworld, you honestly can't go wrong here. The major complaint I've got with it is that it made me want to replay Homeworld 1 again, right when I was gearing up for an XCOM2 re-run. Damn it.EDIT: Updating this review to justify my nomination of this game for the  'I've got something in my eye' award. If you've played the campaign and seen the last few missions in particular.... yep."
76561198020076869,Recommended,281610,20680854,"Posted: 22 January, 2016",all,JadeFalcon777,"Game pretty much perfectly captures the feel of the old Homeworld games.  Campaign is excellent - great visuals, voice acting, and good mission design.Keep in mind that the campaign is the main draw here, though there is a skirmish with AI and multiplayer.  I've seen some complaints about the AI, but it's certainly giving me a challenge on normal."
