,Recommended,281610,24487960,"Posted: 23 July, 2016",all,Destructively Phased,"If, like me, before you bought this game you'd heard that the game didn't match the standard of the other Homeworld games, that it didn't fit the ""Homeworld family"" and that put you off buying the game, let me tell you something. Whoever said that, they were wrong. I will spoil some plot points later, but I will warn in advanceHomeworld: Deserts of Kharak is very much a member of the Homeworld family, and not just a formal it exists way. It's story is strong, with surprise turn arounds and unexpected events, it still carries the ""lone fleet"" feeling of the Homeworld 1 and 2, in fact I'd say that feeling is stronger in this game than it is in Homeworld 2, the constant news of Coalition (the player faction) outposts under attack and Gaalsien force movements creates the feeling of isolation more so than any of HW2 plot. This is further reinforced by the fact that your sole ally in your journey isn't a member of Coalition forces, instead they are Sidiim, another faction on Kharak.One of the most powerful moments of this is the start of a mission, when to come to the aid of stranded fleet units the Carrier overloads it's engines to reach the mission site while they're still intact, the cutscene of the gigantic vessel bouncing over a dune was one of the most powerful moments of the campaign, giving strength to the feeling of the fleet being on it's own with no cavalry comming. This is what Homeworld really is about, the perservation of a single fleet through immense odds.I'll break away from the talk about how HW:DOK plot and story earn it it's rightful place in the Homeworld series to talk about gameplay. It's good, there's nothing quite as enjoyable as launching a cruise missile at the enemy, or ordering all of your fighter wings to bombard enemies that are giving your ground forces a hard time. The rank system where units gain eperience and gain promotions gives you a reason to preserve your units and to care when their destroyed, unlike in the original Homeworlds where the only thing you cared about losing was capital ships due to the extreme cost in replacing them. The rank system doesn't make units OP, for example you aren't going to be facing down a battlecruiser with a single high rank Light Attack Vehicle, but having high ranked units does give you the edge, and it's nice to see a reward for smart tactics than just ""You saved some RP!"".Spoilers from here!Back to the plot and story, again I feel it delivers better, and not in ways that can't be explained by better technology. The main adversary I can understand as to why he declared holy war, his faith felt real, mostly supported by the cutscene for his death, pleading for the players faction to request forgiveness from Sajuuk. The Sidiims betrayal came as a surprise, despite the captain of the Carrier expressing concerns about them in his personal log, but I expected my ally to push to far and get themselves killed in battle in a cutscene, so the shock of watching them blow the aircraft bringing my resupply out of the sky after I'd protected the rock being used as a landing strip for both of us was genuine.The voice acting, while my laptop was constantly garbling half of the spoken audio, what came out ungarbled was a level of quality higher than old homeworld games, not in a higher quality of sound way, but in terms of performance. Concern in the characters voices is common place, theres bitterness in the captains personal log after the Sidiim's betrayal, things that were again missing in the original homeworld games.Homeworld: Deserts of Kharak to me is very much a Homeworld game. It worked hard to get there, but it is one. It's plot powerful, like the old games, it has ways to jump the enemy and embrace power fantasy, similar to how jumping a battlecruiser into the enemy production fleet felt in HW2.Finally, it blends the high speed duels of light craft (LAVs and fighers) with the slow combat of the larger vessels in the Homeworld way, so that while there may be one battle going on, but in that battle there'll be multiple battles going on, each one affecting the overall outcome. At least until you steamroll everything with the OP artillery cruisers, similar to how being the first with battlecruisers in a HW2 match felt.It's pretty much all I can ask for in a Homeworld game."
