76561198065573956,Recommended,281610,20682359,"Posted: 22 January, 2016",all,LtDutchman,"FINALLY a new RTS game on the market! Ignore all those negative reviews, just a bunch of spoiled gamers who only want to play a game they designed in their imagination (but that is just not how it works). I only just met with the Homeland Series and I must say I am really impressed! I love the fact that every unit you create counts, especially in the Campaign, as they gain veterancy and every unit and CU/RU get transfered to the next mission. This veterancy system becomes more and more important as the missions progress, and trust me, you will want high ranking units further in the game! The same goes for Skirmish mode, there is no unit spamming due to the fact that you have to micro manage you resources and research, as well as veterancy. An elite unit will always over power a lower ranked unit. Regardless off what many reviewers on here say about infantry, I also love the fact that it is vehicle combar only, as infantry would be useless due to the massive sizes of the vehicles, (just look at some of the cut-scene's, Rachel sitting under the Science Runner, or when the Runner enters the Epsilon base) so infantry would make no sense .. I agree on the fact that there are not a lot of skirmish maps at the moment but, come on, the game just launched I am sure they will add more in the future! As for NO Base Building, I do not care too much for that. I love the fact that you command a huge carrier which is your mobile FOB and you have to protect it all costs. People also complained that there was not enough advertising before the launch, but I can understand and even prefer that, as too many games over advertise their games and end up with just a lot of fuss .. I can recommend this game to everyone who has missed a proper RTS game (as it is a dying breed), I am really happy to be able to play a new type of RTS without unit spamming. The only thing that does bug me a little is the unit limit, a max fleet of 125 (vehicles can take up to 8 units at once) so that is another point that needs working on (I think it is like that for performance). As for the rest, I think we will some major balance and content updates in the near future and I cannot wait to see them."
76561197968449707,Recommended,281610,20687470,"Posted: 22 January, 2016",all,23-Down,"Homeworld: Deserts of KharakWow the first Homeworld game in over a decade. And while I'm not that happy that it did play on ground this time I still very much enjoyed it.Black Bird Interactive tried to remain loyal to the original art and style which goes from the epic cutscenes including the famous cinema borders + sound to the level of cutscenes while slightly enhanced nowadays you certainly know that this is a Homeworld game so fans of the old series might feel at home right away just in regards of the style.Story:Well there isn't much to tell and I don't want to say much about it but it is a prequel to Homeworld 1 in which you rediscover your origin of your people. While few plot holes and unanswered questions remain the story was well executed and does flow charmingly into the franchise.Gameplay:The game arrives with a decent tech tree and alot of discovery awaits. How ever I felt that the (SP) Missions were somewhat to easy and also to repetiive compared to the masterpieces of the original Homeworld games.As for the factions both of em seem rather balanced and are mostly copying each other. Their animations and looks differ but that's all I could tell during the playthrough of the campaign. (on medium by the way) But that doesn't necessarily make it bad in either way.Terrain also plays a significant role in this game as the line of sight and hight matters which adds some sort of strategic benefit similar to the Ground Control games. Also long range units are of certain importance as well. Because they can mean the difference between defeat and victory. If you're getting caught off guard an enemy air raid might eradicate your ground forces kinda fast if there's no AA nearby. Same goes for Artillery if you lack your own long range units or other counters you might be in for a rough ride. Conclusion it's a fun and rather balanced game with several strategic possibilities.Mp:There isn't much to tell yet as the mp section of the game is very tiny to this point. There're like 5,6 maps total which is kinda sad although I suspect more might follow. The game modi are also limited to (team)deathmatch and artifact recovery which is somewhat similar to capture the flag or king of the hill gaming modes except that you need to deliver the artifacts to a certain drop off point just like in CTF.Most maps are very small which adds a certain tension throughout the match though at the same time I also find it limiting as it doesn't allow you much room to flank your opponents. Also pity that they didn't add in some of their weather effects of the single player missions (Sand storms, Tornados) to the mp maps as that might have added in some additional spice to the mp game sector.Pro:-Lovely story.-Balanced game-Good audio components-Nice graphics-Good performance on a 3 year old Quad Core I5.Contra:-Tiny and limited mp section-Small sp campaign with somewhat repetitive mission design ""Salvage this, destroy that"" kind of thing.- Few plot holes and unanswered questions remained in the story arc (Taiidan? And why did it crash? 1st expedition? What happened to the remaining crew of certain Characters ship?)-Can't modify the controls (yet)(-What do they eat? Not a single plant nor animal seen throughout the game. I know it's a desert planet but at least some alien cactus here and there wont hurt.) Getting answered more closely in the Survival Guide.All in all I can recommend it. Though I would possibly wait till a steam sale. It's good but it's not that good to pay 50 bucks for. Simply because it's a rather small game at this point. If you're a hardcore Homeworld fan though, then yes ""Get it right away"". :P"
,Recommended,281610,20680899,"Posted: 22 January, 2016",all,Squeaks,"This is a good take on an excellent classic. It's a RTS, but it's not in the same vein as the frenzied click-fest style of so many modern RTS's. For the most part, you have time to plan moves, co-ordinate attacks with ground and air assets, long range and repair craft all contributing towards a sucessful maneuver.There are times when it does turn into a panic, and you have to move fast and click even faster, but that's not the norm, and I think it only serves to add tension to an otherwise slower paced RTS.Significient tactical choices are few, but vital. For exmaple, some terrain will not allow the passage of your carrier, so do you leave it unguarded and send the rest of your units off, or split them, losing the punch?I haven't tried mlultiplayer yet, but I can imagine that is a bit more of a click-fest, but still not overwhelmingly so, due to the way the game works. I think that it will be played better on the tactical map for MP than in the close u p pretty view though, so you can keep an eye on what your opponent is up to.The game looks and sounds very good indeed, and although that's not why you buy a strategy game, it does add a lot towards the value of it.Overall, I'd recommend this game as rewarding and fun to play, but not a serious challange, at least in SP mode."
