,Recommended,281610,20747354,"Posted: 25 January, 2016",all,Zakalwe,"I sort of recommend this game. For the price, there's little content to keep you going long term (5 maps??), and the unit type and population cap limit the scope of the game. Much like Homeworld though, there's something a bit special about this game.The low unit cap and mix means that the game is a micromanager's dream come true. Launching a gunship is a real event, if only because you have access to so few, while that isolated handful of tanks on the perimiter becomes increasingly precious as damage is taken from waves of enemy units. It's a little like Dawn of War 2 in many ways, though no where near as developed.I've heard the game called a Beta, and I'd agree with this. The resource wrecks are all copy/paste efforts for the same model, for example. Work needs to be done on the skirmish AI, though it's not quite as bad as some say. Personally, I find the carrier base to be slightly ridiculous and far too derivitive of an actual aircraft carrier. The design feels lazy and uninspired. It's unfortunate that it's got Ashes of the Singularity's lovely capital ships to be compared to at the moment. All in all, this feels like a game that needed a few more months of design and polishing.Despite these negatives, the game is a lot fun. The effects and sound have real oomph to them, and combat is very rewarding.  There's still a lot of work to be done before the game justifies its high price tag, and I'd expect to see a lot of free content to go in before we start on paid DLC, but this is one of the better RTS games to come out recently."
