76561197967795441,Recommended,281610,21443947,"Posted: 25 February, 2016",all,phasemaster,"When I first loaded upHomeworld: Deserts of Kharakand dove into the first mission, I knew it felt right within seconds. The technical sci-fi unit chatter was there, the strategic overlay was a familiar blue with helpful unit icons, and my fleet was setting off into the emptiness ofspacethe desert.DoKis a love song to the original 1999Homeworldin all of the best ways.  Although I found myself missing the Z-axis, the rest of the Homeworld formula remained quite intact--from the strike/armored/ranged/cruiser unit types to the versatile camera movement. It also speaks to the fluid controls that I was able to play the entire game easily with a Steam Controller :)The story inDoKalso does a great job of mirroring the great continuity that was present from mission to mission in vanillaHomeworld.  You are not jumping around the planet/galaxy on various missions like in aStarcraftorC&Cgame--it is just your fleet on a long, difficult journey.  And true to the 1999 original's legacy, your fleet persists from mission to mission, so units left alive at the end of a battle are able to continue on in the campaign (now with helpful veterancy bonuses).One place where I was a little disappointed was with the difficulty ofDoK.  Although the campaign's strong narrative does a good job of making youfeela sense of urgency, I found that I was able to take losses and keep going way more than I could in the originalHomeworld--even on Hard difficulty.  This lack of extreme difficulty also made the game effectively shorter for me (17 hours for the campaign) than its 1999 brother, even though I think the number of campaign missions was comparable.The easier difficulty could be partly due to lulls in the fighting that allow ample time for your salvagers to hoover up every last resource in the AO--a tactic that was essential in 1999Homeworld--so I was rarely wanting for resources.  But I really only found myself sweating before I had built up a fleet in some of the early missions, and in a couple cases where my fleet was not available on account of some smaller scale missions.But I have a fix for these gripes.  I was not planning on getting theHomeworld: Remastered Collectionbefore; butDoKhas left me so thirsty for the brand of storytelling that has been true of all of theHomeworldgames that I cannot resist grabbing the Remaster at this point."
,Recommended,281610,21514345,"Posted: 27 February, 2016",all,Etheras,"A somewhat-unconventional take on the RTS genre, Homeworld: Deserts of Kharak is an interesting new installment into the Homeworld franchise from the writers who brought you the original Homeworld. I enjoyed it immensely, but then again, I am a bit of a strategy game fanboy, so I tend to give a little extra credit to strategy games. Keep that in mind if you're on-the-fence.The GoodGRAPHICS : The graphics are spectacular. Nice high-poly units, great animations on the missiles and machine-guns. But beyond anything else; holy crap the volumetric smoke and dust clouds are better than I've seen in any other gameever. Check my screenshot library to see what I mean. Explosions too are very compelling.STYLE : The art style is absolutely breathtaking. With the middle-eastern inspired music, that also really helps to set itself apart. The people all in their gasmasks and the massive-scale everything (even the smallest vehicles are crazy-big), and the look of giant carriers rolling across the desert - brilliant!STORY : It has an interesting military sci-fi feel, with all the big carriers being named, the map locations being named, a very interesting enemy force - radical zealots protecting anomalies in the desert, while wearing creepy gas mask things but enjoying technology far greater than your own group.CUTSCENES : Fully-rendered cutscenes between each level that are absolutely gorgeous.ENVIRONMENT : I heard complaints (specifically from Total Biscuit, whom I highly respect) about the lack of terrain variety. I must disagree on this one. Its true that all of the levels are desert, but that's sort-of important to the story. Also - I'd like to see the practicality of giant rolling carriers in, say, a jungle. Good luck with that. But regardless... Its all deserts, but there are a great variety of deserts. Some have big sandy dunes, others have rocky chasms and plateaus, others are mining areas filled with derelicst and holes, and you even have a desert city level.2D MAPS : This is probably blasphemy to consider this a plus for a Homeworld game, but I really disliked the 3D combat of Homeworld. I found it difficult to control, and difficult to judge distances. Deserts of Kharak solves that problem by simply removing the 3rd dimension, which really simplifies the UI and makes it easier to enjoy the game.The BadGAMEPLAY IN-GENERAL : Controls aren't very tight. Part of this is due, I think, to an attempt to simulate real-world physics in the movement of the units. However, they are all incredibly sluggish.UNIT AI : I realize that this is a hard thing to do, and I gripe about it a lot, but AI can be the difference between victory and defeat. And is also the most common reason for me to shout at the screen when its being stupid. So - in this game, the units aren't very good at retreating. You tell a cruiser to get to the back of the line for repairs, and it does a 3-point turn like a student driver (that is: like an 8 point turn). Other units coming up to replace said damaged unit proceed to ram into it, preventing it from getting to the back line. They get stuck. Meanwhile, the unit is still taking damage, and eventually dies, even though it had at least an order of magnitude more time than it needed to get to the repair area.NO MINIMAP : I realize this is homeworld, so they wanted to utilize the spacebar tactical screen mechanic, but a minimap would be helpful. Since this is a 2D world-scape, there's no reason not to have one.KINDA BUGGY : Especially multiplayer. During one game, I was not given the ability to ever increase my unit cap. Obviously this put me at a massive disadvantage. Another game, the guy mining RUs continued to mine (I could see the number going down), but it was not being added to my inventory. Then BOOM all at once I get like 200 RU. Finally, the physics are a little wonky sometimes. I had two  occasions where my carrier actually flew up off the ground, flipped around, and was doing all kinds of crazy acrobatics. Both times it eventually settled back down.PRICE : Sort-of the elephant in the room. The game is not long. There's probably only about 10-12 missions in the campaign. The multiplayer also has maybe 10 maps, but the weakness in gameplay probably won't foster a long-term multiplayer experience. Like the original homeworld, its the story that really sells this game, so you need to weigh the price against the length of the campaign. I personally would say that $60 (which is how much I paid), it a bit steep. I think $20-$25 is probably a better price point.ConclusionDeserts of Kharak is a fun but flawed extension on the Homeworld franchise. Perhaps this means we will be getting more of them? I do suspect that the short length of the primary campaign may be a sign that there are DLCs in the works. If that's the case, it might be worth waiting until an Ultimate Edition (considering the price). But for us rich gamers who don't mind paying top-dollar for an enjoyable experience - I'd give Homeworld Deserts of Kharak a 7/10 .Thanks for reading!"
