,Recommended,281610,21599603,"Posted: 3 March, 2016",all,Critical Hit,"I've just purchased this game, I haven't put very much time into it but I can spot an amazing game when I see one. This game is fantastic. As a huge fan of the original Homeworld games, I was cautious about a Homeworld prequel game, especially given the fact that the game was being developed by someone other than the original developers, Relic. My fears appear to have been unfounded. What struck me immediately was the tone and feel of Homeworld: Deserts of Kharak. It's pitch perfect, completely reminicent of the original games. Everything, down to the music, effects and even the comm chatter between units...it's all so great. I've played 3 of the campaign missions thus far, and the gameplay is fantastic. Controls are smooth, intuitive, simple and easy to use. Combat requires a bit of strategy (for example, using terrain for a height advantage, using unit abilities to turn the tide of a battle) and it's challenging but for me the bottom line is always...is it fun? YES, yes it is. Given what I've seen thus far, I am so pleased that the Homeworld series appears to have risen from the dead. The series appears to be in the capable hands of Blackbird Interactive and Gearbox Software and if this game is any indication of what the future might hold...the future of Homeworld seems bright indeed. I'll likely update this review as I get further into the campaign and try out the Skirmish mode, but as of this moment I highly, highly recommend to anyone who loved the original Homeworld games or fans of RTS games in general. Go buy it!"
,Recommended,281610,20912100,"Posted: 2 February, 2016",all,Waspus,"TL;DRGame is fun. Units are well thought out and the game is welcoming of many different strategies. Campaign could be longer, there could be more skirmish maps, but overall quite fun for any RTS fan.Long ReviewSome of the top reviews for this game are negative. I'm not sure what angle they're coming at the game or what their background on RTS games is, but I can assure you that if you're an RTS fan, especially if you're a Homeworld fan, you will enjoy this game.It plays very similar to Starcraft in terms of unit construction, resource gathering, giving orders to units and other aspects. If you're looking for a grand-scale RTS like Supreme Commander, Total War, Age of Empires / Mythology or anything like that, don't even consider this game. It's decidedly very small-scale.The main object of the gaim is centered around these giant, land-going aircraft carriers. We won't discuss the necessity of such a device, but the aim is to protect your own and destroy your enemy's. They have very high health but poor defense systems, and can be upgraded in a variety of ways by ""shunting"" power to their various systems, including weapons, armor and repairs.Next, you have small units, which are Salvagers, LAVs, and Baserunners. Salvagers gather resources, known as CUs and RUs, that allow you to construct new units and purchase upgrades for your existing ones. LAVs are your basic combat vehicle that can be upgraded to a miniscule extent over time, and Baserunners do a variety of things including deploying turrets, AA batteries, and collecting Artifacts, one of the objectives in Skirmish mode.Then you have your heavy vehicles. Missile batteries, railguns, and armored assault vehicles. I don't use these too much so the best extent I can describe them to is that they are simply more powerful, slower-moving LAVs.Next are your aerial vehicles; interceptors, gunships, and bombers. They are deployed from your aircraft carrier and all serve to attack ground targets. They move quickly and deal surprisingly high damage. They're actually a bit overpowered if you ask me.Finally, you have cruisers. Support cruisers, battlecruisers, assault cruisers and artillery cruisers. Support cruisers act as mobile drop-off points for resources, so they're good for resource gathering operations that are far away from your carrier, and the other three are basically giant, slow-moving attack vehicles that deal very high damage, especially to large groups.As I stated before, this game is very friendly towards many different strategies and playstyles. You can check out some gameplay videos on youtube, including ones that I may or may not put up in the future to get a better idea of the gameplay.The campaign is fun, if short, and offers a few new units and abilities that you can't get in Skirmish mode, namely different types of Baserunners with different abilities. The missions are all pretty much ""Move from this point to this point, fight off wave after wave of enemy, and collect resources along the way"". You do get to keep your constructed units and upgrades from mission to mission, so that's a nice touch.The story is interesting and the art is very nice too. Nobody plays RTS games for the graphics so I'll leave it at ""The art style is nice"". Some people in the reviews down below complained of stuttering, I haven't experienced that myself but I do have an absolute beast of a PC (980 Ti / 6700k) so exercise caution. Turning down the graphics if you have to really doesn't hinder your experience.The AI could stand to be better, I play on normal difficulty in both skirmish and campaign, and its strategy in skirmish mode anyway is to send wave after wave of Sandskimmers (Small, light attack vehicles) that are instantly dispatched by my cruisers.In all, this is a fun game, a bit lacking for the price but what can you do. I definitely recommend it, you will have fun whether you pay $6 or $60."
