,Recommended,281610,20898074,"Posted: 1 February, 2016",all,Misty,"Let me start by saying that for any Homeworld fan this game is a no-brainer.If you have never played Homeworld, expect a strategy game that gives you control over a roughly 500m long ground-based airship and a large fleet, all set in the endless deserts of Kharak.Construction & CombatThe airship serves as both your main vehicle and a recruitment base. From that point on, it's up to you. Just like in most RTS games, you are offered a variety of vehicles for construction, each with a unique set of specs. What I really like about this game tough is the fact that the result of a contact with the enemy fleet varies not only upon the obvious quantity and unit types but also positioning, as the game incorporates the terrain as a factor (highground v. lowground).UIThe interface is very user-friendly. There is no opening of all the menus in order to find that one specific button. Everything is nicely organised and easy to control.Campaign & SkirmishHaving not finished the campaign yet, I cannot really tell how the story will advance. However, from this point I would say the story is rather simple, so do not expect anything beyond average complexity. It is also being told using personal logs at the end of each mission. Another downside is the fact that if you want to play a skirmish, you only have 4 maps and 2 factions to choose from.Where Homeworld excels though is narration. The quality of the voiceover is brilliant, the units change there voices according to the sitiuation they are in and along with the great background music, you really get a feeling of the ongoing conflict.In conclusion, Homeworld: Deserts of Kharak is a great prequel to the Homeworld series and even with some reserves it is worth getting."
