,Recommended,281610,20878109,"Posted: 31 January, 2016",all,Deadpool,"Truly lives up to the Homeworld name. Not a sequel riding on the coattails of the original's success. However, recommend watching videos of gameplay before buying./// Potential Spoilers ///A few things that could use some polish: AI, objective time/progression, resource availability, and the length of the campaign. Note this is from the perspective of someone who generally plays games at their maximum difficulty, in a single campaign playthrough on classic difficulty.The AI suffers from predictability, which makes it very easy to outmaneuver the opposing force. Many times, if you hunker down to delay the progress of objectives, you can farm experience for your troops by picking off endless enemy waves. Eventually, you can even employ a similar tactic to steal enemy troops and bolster your own forces beyond the logistical limit. This is made easier by the fact that enemy waves usually have a poor composition of armor, firepower, and support capabilities not tailored to what they'll be facing.As mentioned above, objectives can be put off indefinitely. One primary example is the shipbreaking in Tombs of the Ancients. Gaalsien forces will not proceed to excavate artifacts or resources until your forces are in close proximity. Time isn't a question, so much that even on classic difficulty a conservative, defensive strategy will almost always prevail.An exception to this lack of pressure is the beginning of The Whispering Gallery. Carrier Sakala is getting slammed by two Gaalsien carriers, cruise missiles, heavy cruisers, strike fighters, bombers, and a mix of ground forces. You must provide immediate assistance to suppress or stall the enemy advance and protect the Sakala while establishing a defensive perimeter around your carrier, the Kapisi. Until the enemy carriers call for a retreat, this part of the mission provides a great change of pace from the rest of the game.Bottom line, resources are abundant. After you get a few maps under your belt, there's really no need to budget Construction Units (CUs), and while the more rare and valuable Resource Units (RUs) are comparatively balanced, eventually it's the same thing. I never had to ask, ""Which research project is worth the cost?"" It was a matter of, ""What do I want first?"" If the enemy AI were improved upon to deny the player these resources, either by aggressively assaulting salvagers or strip mining it themselves (a scorched earth strategy), this could be less of an issue. Otherwise, it really feels less like you're trying to survive. In an expedition across a massive wasteland. Virtually alone. Deep inside enemy territory.Lastly, I've seen other reviews claim the campaign was too short, providing too little content for the asking price. While there may be some truth to this, the campaign felt neither rushed, nor dragged out over pointless filler maps. Every mission had its place in the story. That's really what I think is the heart of Homeworld: Deserts of Kharak, the story. If the story were to be expanded on, it would be worth seeing a parallel campaign from the Gaalsien perspective, or standalone missions demonstrating significant historical events of Kharak.That's my two cents. I am still quite pleased with the game."
