76561198047169453,Recommended,281610,20985948,"Posted: 5 February, 2016",all,DeinonychusCowboy,"I'm recommending this game, but a bit tentatively.I've been a homeworld fan since around 2001, and am in the camp that thoroughly enjoyed the remastered version. While I'm overjoyed to see the original developers back in control of the IP and doing new things with it, I don't think this game ended up being what I wanted it to be.It's a ground-based RTS that tries to be like the space-based games in some respects. This works well in some ways, but is a bit odd in others. Aircraft, the units most like units in the original games, are pretty nuked, and maneuvering/management of ground units is less seamlessly intuitive than fleet management in 2 or RM. I found myself playing a LOT of the game out of the sensors manager, because it was too difficult to get a strategic view from the main camera.When I heard BBI got the rights to use the Homeworld Universe and was going to turn Hardware: Shipbreakers into a prequel, I was most excited to see them draw on the existing body of backstory from the first game. This they certainly did in spades; the main antagonist of the game is discussed at length in the original game's manual, and indeed I went back to read my ~15-year-old copy to understand the plot better. They did a great job fitting the campaign's plot into the existing mythos, and even the retcons make perfect sense and don't feel weird given the plot of the first game.However, though the campaign story was exactly the one I wanted to be told, I don't think it was told very well. All the events I wanted to see happened on-screen and seemed to make sense within the mythos, but some of them just felt... awkward. The game seemed to expect players to be familiar with the plot of the first game, and so did not conceal critical information or make certain assumptions that I think should have been in place in the first half of the campaign. The main voices in the game transitioned far too rapidly from early exposition to a mentality that seemed more suited to AFTER the game's plot, and seemed to demonstrate knowledge of a certain ship's specific nature well before they should have known or even guessed that information. I would have really liked to see this story told with a greater degree of unfamiliarity and doubt on the part of the characters; it would have made the wonder of the final revelation much more dramatic, the way I always pictured it when playing the first game.I also found the campaign painfully short. Homeworld is known for its short campaigns that give you just enough to invest you, not enough to satisfy you, but the norm is 16 or 17 missions. HW:DoK has 13. I could point out specific parts of the map that I feel could have had additional missions.Overall, the campaign felt rushed, and some of the game mechanics feel somewhat underdeveloped. I would have loved to see more done with the heat mechanic, for example. The unit designs don't present as cohesive of a theme as the original game's did, and though I give BBI props for recreating the 'feel' of 2 nearly seamlessly in a completely different game engine (Unity), the graphics didn't blow my mind and make me squee the way HW:RM's did.So, why am I recommending this game if I'm giving it so much flak? A couple reasons. Firstly, I think some of the game's limitations are due to the nature of its production. I almost feel like it would have been a better game if BBI had NOT gotten the rights to the IP, though I'm still glad they did. I'm not sure this game was ready to be ""the next Homeworld game"", though it could have been an interesting game in its own right.Secondly, it's hardly a bad game. I'm not as into ground-based RTSes, but it's well-balanced (though, knowing the homeworld fanbase, I'm sure everyone and his mom will disagree) and has a number of different effective strategies. The combat is fast-paced and dynamic, and the lack of base-building and presence of universal unit mobility really makes it feel like a homeworld game in some regards.Thirdly, they did tell the story I wanted to be told, and didn't make any fatal retcons. For comparison, I felt HW2 was actually worse about this - in 2 it's established that the hyperspace core used in the mothership is 'special', and to do this they had to retcon parts of the original game's manual that mentioned it being 'reverse-engineered' and scaled up to handle the mothership's mass. I also felt 2's endgame made some bad choices about the direction of the universe and some of the explanations for its mechanics. DoK did much better about this - Kharak is Kharak. My inner cartography nerd was even squeeing when recognizing geographic/stylistic elements I remembered from reading the manual as a kid.I'm excited to see what BBI does next with the property, and I think existing Homeworld fans should play this game, more for closure than anything else. However, don't come into it expecting the atmospheric/mood quality of the original Homeworld or the mechanical polish of 2/RM. You'll be very disappointed."
