76561198005679221,Recommended,281610,26887242,"Posted: 23 November, 2016",all,Furvel,"This game is very immersive. The attention on detail is very thorough. Vehicles chatter among themselves and give clues on how a fight is going. Parts move separately from eachother on each unit, tires have suspension and miniguns rotate. It is very rewarding to zoom close in and watch.The storytelling is top tier and tells a story where you can argue the merits of all sides in the conflict, no easy good vs evil setting.Multiplayer is different from the singleplayer in that it is very fast paced. Don´t expect to have time to adore scenery midcombat, to alleviate that there is a replay function. The multiplayer also feels different in that it is in a confined space, where the single player had the journey as a focal point. The multiplayer felt more like a close combat brawl where units dodge and weave behind sand dunes to avoid line of sight (yes there is cover and height advantage) and reappear to give a quick jab and take out a straggling unit.The mechanics of the game seems simple at first glance, the amount of units in the tiers give the impression that it is the usual Rock Paper Scissors deal with counters, but it goes deeper with upgrades and overlapping functions on some units.A minor negative is that there is no collision detection, you cannot hide weaker units behind stronger, and shots travel right through friendly units but not sand dunes. It gives an odd impression when everything is so polished and then two units clip into eachother. Another negative is more of a preferance, but skirmish is easy when you get the hang of it (even vs hard AI) and multiplayer is very fast paced and has a steep learning curve.If you get this game on sale it is very much worth it. The dlc:s are variations of the two base armies and adds to the deeper tactics in multiplayer/skirmish only."
76561198011206383,Recommended,281610,26651057,"Posted: 17 November, 2016",all,Madeyes2882,"It's like old Homeworld, but on the ground! Not really...but actually yes some strong similarities, which at first led me to think ""why not just devote the resources (RUs..) to a new game with the more traditional format we're used to?"" However once I dove in I found myself really enjoying this iteration of the game universe. As with the other games we have the same artfully crafted enviroments coupled with amazing cinematics and strong narration and VO work. Add to that simple to pick up mechanics and increasingly fast paced missions (Im a little over half way through) and you have exaustive and addictive gameplay. The usual ""rock, paper, scissor"" feel of most RTS' is present, however a wide unit base and numerous special abilties makes every engagement interesting.Perhaps the biggest improvement over previous HM games is your ""mother ship"" (in this case, Command Carrier). Gone are the slow lumbering targets of the past; the Carrier eventually becomes an honest to god fighting ship and a mastery of its extensive abilities and aircraft is essential to success.For a long time Homeworld junkie like me this is another great addition to the series, however I look forward to hopefully returning to the stars next time."
