,Recommended,281610,28367971,"Posted: 14 December, 2016",all,TheEnemy,"As an alternate setting for the Homeworld theme and look, this game captures the feeling of it quite well. If you're a fan of Homeworld, read on. The storytelling and narrative form follows the same principles as the Homeworld games and I grew a bit attached to my carrier and Rachel over the course of the campaign. Still, don't expect any masterwork storytelling here, it's decent at most and why I would only recommend it getting it on sale.The visuals are quite pleasing, despite being on a desert planet there's nice variation in terrain, the sand dunes both look good and work as line of sight blocking for units. All the units are nicely detailed and they leave lots of tracks in the sand.The gameplay is as any other RTS, though a bit more rock-paper-scissors than most. You can collect artifacts to improve your carrier over the campaign, giving a nice sense of progress besides getting access to new units. The campaign is not a challenge at all, though maybe it's because I took the time to collect pretty much all resources, meaning I never ran out. I only loaded on two occasions, once when an entire army spawned right on top of my carrier (the only example of bad scripting I encountered) and a second time when a mission ended before I had checked one last location for a possible artifact (read aforementioned comment about harvesting everything). I was really missing a speed up function while harvesting though and it made the campaign feel much longer than it actually was.The length of the campaign was fine, but I would have liked a few more missions spending some more time on lore and the relationship between the factions of the planet.In the end, I enjoyed the game and it had the right Homeworld feel, so if you liked Homeworld and want more, go ahead and pick it up on sale.Final words (spoiler alert):My biggest gripe with the story is that a big part of it contradicts the start of the original Homeworld. There their planet is attacked because they violated an old treaty, that they knew nothing about. That's the whole precondition for the start of the Homeworld story - and here they talk about it all the time."
