,Recommended,281610,33566582,Posted: 15 July,all,Mazian,"At a discount, this is a good purchase.DISCLAIMER:I only played the campaign, and I played almost exclusively for the story. I had little interest in MP.SUMMARY:Deserts of Kharak (DoK) returns to the Homeworld formula, this time in 2d instead of 3d. This prequal returns to the time immediately prior to the original Homeworld, when the inhabitents of the desert world of Kharak are fighting amongst themselves over ideological differences-- science vs religion. While Homeworld presented a mostly united planet, set about the mission of discovering the origins of the species (for it was not their current planet, as they had long believed), DoK sets out retelling the story of the Kushan's final (?) war on Kharak prior to the unification that led to the Mothership Project being possible.PROS:* Persistent armies between missions, unit experience & advancement, a diverse unit list, a diverse faction list (really only useful in multiplayer), well narrated in-mission and inter-mission voice segments, an appealing aesthetic (kind of a comic-book feel to the inter-mission cutscenes), and a well scripted story that fit perfectly in to the Homeworld narrative.CONS:* Units are not very balanced. The solution to most fights is to mass cruisers with sufficient support to repair through all but overwhelming odds (and for that, sacrifice cruise missiles and air strikes to thin them out before crushing them underwheel.) The story is very short (8 hours to play through the first time). The artifacts that grant certain bonuses during campaign gameplay are not easily identified-- you have to scour the entire map and ""shipbreak"" the debris to find them all. The most valuable of the artifacts are the ones that decrease logistics costs, the rest are almost pointless on easy difficulty. However, there is no specific directive mechanic to ensure that you collect the critical relics. Additionally, towards the end of the campaign you are given 'superweapons' that reduce you to fighting defensively while your superweapons do the rest of the fighting for you-- and last, and worst, the AI is poorly written and balanced-- it will let you demolish units with artillery from afar without reprisal; it will churn out units endless, not held to any economic mechanic; The AI is not limited by line of sight and will throw endless waves of air strikes against you; the AI is not limited by unit speeds and is able to micro units to ensure squad cohension (unlike players). Lastly, technically the game does not render properly on a wide screen monitor. It has verticle bands on the left and right during inter-mission cutscenes and load scenes that show the PC desktop background sometimes (or Steam overlay may sometimes appear.) In-mission renders properly but not at the maximum resolution of my monitor.CONCLUSION:While I'm happy to see another addition to the Homeworld IP, and I appreciate all of the improvements over the original Homeworld UI, the game feels essentially like a retread of original Homeworld IP with a minimally updated UI. There are a number of parallels to Homeworld, including how certain scenes are presented, and how certain plot elements unfold. While I'm not opposed to formulaic stories, I could wish for a little originality when it comes to blending the formula for a new narrative. Being a prequal and on-planet is a nice spin, but by itself not sufficient to warrant unreserved praise.I think the metacritic score is justly awarded. I would recommend any fan of the Homeworld series to purchase it, but I would recommend you wait till its on sale (or until the price comes down to <$20.)"
